    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm struggling with some of the concepts for my undergrad physics midterm. can u explain quantum entanglement in simple terms? like, what's the main difference between that and just regular classical correlation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, imagine you're in a forest, and you have two magical, talking trees, let's call them Tree A and Tree B. Now, these trees are not just any trees; they have a special bond. If you whisper a secret to Tree A, Tree B will instantly know and whisper back the same secret, even if they're miles apart. This is like quantum entanglement. In the quantum world, particles can be entangled, meaning the state of one particle instantly influences the state of another, no matter the distance between them. This is different from classical correlation, where two things might be related, but they don't share secrets instantly. It's like if you and your friend both have a map of the forest, but you can't whisper secrets to each other. The trees (particles) are the magical, talking trees (entangled particles) that share secrets (states) instantly.",
