    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but i heard einstein called it 'spooky action at a distance.' why did he call it spooky? is there something actually weird or unsettling about how it works?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, Einstein, the great skeptic, indeed called it \"spooky action at a distance.\" He found it unsettling because it seemed to defy the very fabric of reality as he understood it. Imagine if you had a pair of enchanted goblins, Goblin A and Goblin B. If Goblin A decided to dance, Goblin B would instantly start dancing too, even if they were on opposite sides of the world. Einstein couldn't wrap his mind around how this could happen without some hidden, unseen goblin magic. He believed that there must be some hidden rule or mechanism that we didn't understand yet, something that would make this \"spooky\" connection possible. In essence, Einstein was uncomfortable with the idea that information could travel faster than the speed of light, which is what quantum entanglement seems to suggest. It's like having a secret goblin whisper that can travel faster than a speeding goblin messenger. To Einstein, this was a mystery that needed to be unraveled, and he famously said, \"God does not play dice with the universe.\" But as it turns out, the universe does play dice, and sometimes, the dice are entangled goblins.",
